<head>BRUSH</head>
    <list type="altnames">
<item>HAIRBRUSH</item>
<item>TOOTHBRUSH</item>
<item>PAINTBRUSH</item>
<item>SCRUB BRUSH</item>
<item>WHISK BROOM</item>
<item>SWEEPER</item>
<item>BROOM</item>
    </list>
    <list type="translations">
        <item xml:lang="zh">刷</item>
    </list>
<div type="definition">
<p>TOOL CONTAINING a HANDLE AND HAIR OR RESEMBLING THINGS FIXED ON that HANDLE.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. Shuǎ 刷 refers to a a miniature broom, typically to a hair brush; the word is quite rare.</p>
<p>2. Bǐ 筆 refers specifically to the writing brush, and the writing brush was in use already in oracle bone times; the word is not common in pre-Han times, but is very frequent for example in LH.</p>
        </div>
